<h3>Sierra Payload Bay</h3>
<h4>Project Manager: Patrick Wasz</h4>
<h4>Project Manager: Jason Wilensky</h4>

<p>The Sierra Payload Bay was an avionics bay designed to collect data and transmit it over the air for the purpose of flying on our Phase II rocket. The sensing unit was controlled by a Raspberry Pi Model B+, which was connected to a GPS receiver, barometric altimeter, and 9-DOF inertial measurement unit. It was mounted on a 3D-printed avionics sled. The data was recorded on the RPi, and a portion of it was sent over a serial port to an XBee S3B 900HP, a 900 MHz band 250mW transmitter. In order to transmit this data over the necessary distance of 2 miles reliably, the team developed a pair of high-gain antennas to increase the transmission’s range. Both were 4-turn, axial-mode helical antennas made of solid copper and supported by a high density polyethylene structure. Hecker transformers were applied to the base of the helix to decrease the impedance of the antennas to an optimal 50 ohms. The units achieved a transmission range of 4 miles in testing.</p>

